article.headline: Air Force 78, IPFW 66
article.story: AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo. (AP) -- Air Force rode a near-perfect shooting performance by Dan Nwaelele to a 78-66 win over Indiana Purdue-Fort Wayne on Saturday. The 6-foot-5 senior forward from Bothell, Wash., hit six of seven field goals, including three of three 3-point attempts, and went 11-for-11 from the free throw line en route to a career-high 26 points. His only miss was on a desperation drive to the hoop a split second before the shot clock expired. "I was just focused out there and my teammates were looking for me," Nwaelele said. "Our team is unselfish and we're always looking for each other in passing the ball. If somebody's open, and somebody else has a better shot, somebody's going to pass you the ball and hopefully you can knock it down." Nwaelele converted free throws at key times in the game to keep a tenacious IPFW (3-5) from overtaking the Falcons (8-1), and his consecutive 3-pointers midway through the second half may have put the game out of the Mastadons' reach. "We've been practicing shooting free throws a lot," he said. "That really paid off." Air Force had taken an early lead, and led 34-29 at the half, but IPFW used strong outside shooting to keep the Falcons from pulling away until late in the game. Jakari Johnson sank five of nine 3-point attempts in leading IPFW scorers with 19 points. Forward Scott DeWitt made three of four 3-pointers, to finish with 15 points. The game was closer than may have been expected following Air Force's convincing 94-58 win over Wake Forest on Wednesday, but Falcons coach Jeff Bzdelik wasn't really surprised. "IPFW is a very well-coached team. They're juniors and seniors, they've played on the road, they've had some big wins. I think people don't really understand who they are and what they're about, so I expected this to be a real battle," Bzdelik said. Bzdelik said the Falcons may have been affected by the praise following the Wake Forest win and by taking a day off to concentrate on school and catch up. "As a basketball team, we need to be rock solid. Our basketball team has to operate on all cylinders," he said. Nwaelele's effort is the highest individual points total for Air Force this season. His previous high was 23. Guard Tim Anderson, the only non-senior among Air Force starters, finished with 18 points and had a career-high four steals. Jacob Burtschi added 14 points. Air Force returns to action Wednesday, hosting Texas Pan-American. IPFW travels to Michigan State on Wednesday.
